  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "A set of **distillation vessels** (*destilleerketels*) made of **Wedgwood Queen's Ware** (cream-coloured earthenware / creamware), used in the chemistry laboratory of **Martinus van Marum** (1750–1837), founding director of Teylers Museum. Van Marum established the **first dedicated chemistry laboratory in the Netherlands** in 1790 in a building adjacent to the museum, using it to demonstrate and extend Lavoisier's oxygen-based chemistry to Dutch audiences.\n\nQueen's Ware is the refined creamware body perfected by **Josiah Wedgwood I** (1730–1795) from c.1765, named after Queen Charlotte (who granted permission to use the name from 1767). Wedgwood was a well-documented supplier of laboratory apparatus — retorts, crucibles, evaporating dishes — to leading 18th-century chemists including Priestley and Lavoisier. These vessels were almost certainly acquired for van Marum's 1790 laboratory programme.",
      "classified_as": [
        {
